      "e3usn": "The diviner unfurls a preserved (or conjured) birthâcaul and scrutinizes its whorls. The target of this proficiency can mitigate 2H wounds of vital damage. If anyone or anything attempts to inflict the target with vital damage, that damage is simply ignored (as if this proficiency acts as a sort of shield).Â ",
      "e3usn-value": "<p>The diviner unfurls a preserved (or conjured) birthâcaul and scrutinizes its whorls. The target of this proficiency can <strong><em>mitigate</em></strong> 2H wounds of vital damage. If anyone or anything attempts to inflict the target with vital damage, that damage is simply ignored (as if this proficiency acts as a sort of shield).Â </p>",
      "61l9a": "Since antiquity, midwives prized the caulâthe translucent amniotic veil sometimes sheathing a newbornâs headâas a numinous chart of the childâs destiny. Roman matronae preserved it in salt, reading minute folds to foretell prosperity or untimely peril, while sailors bought dried cauls as talismans against drowning, believing the membrane that once cocooned life could still ward the sea. Medieval cunning women and Scottish âwise wifiesâ consulted cauls to diagnose infant maladies and divine a householdâs fortunes for the coming year. Renaissance physicians like Paracelsus wrote of signatura hidden in the caulâs marbling, linking its patterns to humoral imbalances. Though later denounced as superstition, the practice endured in rural Europe well into the nineteenth century, whispered of as âveilâscrying.â",
      "61l9a-value": "<p><br data-start=\"83\" data-end=\"86\" />Since antiquity, midwives prized the <em data-start=\"123\" data-end=\"129\" data-is-only-node=\"\">caul</em>âthe translucent amniotic veil sometimes sheathing a newbornâs headâas a numinous chart of the childâs destiny. Roman matronae preserved it in salt, reading minute folds to foretell prosperity or untimely peril, while sailors bought dried cauls as talismans against drowning, believing the membrane that once cocooned life could still ward the sea. Medieval <em data-start=\"487\" data-end=\"502\">cunning women</em> and Scottish âwise wifiesâ consulted cauls to diagnose infant maladies and divine a householdâs fortunes for the coming year. Renaissance physicians like Paracelsus wrote of <em data-start=\"677\" data-end=\"688\">signatura</em> hidden in the caulâs marbling, linking its patterns to humoral imbalances. Though later denounced as superstition, the practice endured in rural Europe well into the nineteenth century, whispered of as âveilâscrying.â</p>"
