      "e3usn-value": "<p>The diviner understands the deep and vital resonance of a bonded pet and can, once per the lifetime of the creature, grant it +1H wound capacity for the rest of its life. This can only be attempted once per creature per lifetime. This can be attempted on pets of allies.Â </p>",
      "61l9a": "Greek magoi coined apantomancy from apanthanein, âto chance upon,â discerning omens in whatever creature or object first crossed oneâs path. Roman augurs weighed the portent of barking dogs, oneâeyed men, or stray cats at dawn, their noteâbooks bristling with graded auspices. Medieval wayfarers watched the roadâs first passerâbyâmonk, crone, or redâhaired youthâto judge whether the day promised profit or peril. Renaissance grimoires codified entire bestiaries of chanceâencounters: a hare on the left betokened betrayal; a blackbird alighting south augured sudden windfall. Though later mocked as mere superstition, sailors, gamblers, and hedgeâwitches still mutter luckâcharms based on whatever apparition greets them at the threshold.",
      "61l9a-value": "<p><br data-start=\"93\" data-end=\"96\" />Greek magoi coined <em data-start=\"115\" data-end=\"128\" data-is-only-node=\"\">apantomancy</em> from <em data-start=\"134\" data-end=\"147\">apanthanein</em>, âto chance upon,â discerning omens in whatever creature or object first crossed oneâs path. Roman augurs weighed the portent of barking dogs, oneâeyed men, or stray cats at dawn, their noteâbooks bristling with graded auspices. Medieval wayfarers watched the roadâs first passerâbyâmonk, crone, or redâhaired youthâto judge whether the day promised profit or peril. Renaissance grimoires codified entire bestiaries of chanceâencounters: a hare on the left betokened betrayal; a blackbird alighting south augured sudden windfall. Though later mocked as mere superstition, sailors, gamblers, and hedgeâwitches still mutter luckâcharms based on whatever apparition greets them at the threshold.</p>"
