      "61l9a": "Sprung from the Greekâ¯amathos (âsandâ), amathomancy bid ancient seers cast sand or graveâash upon marble to read the errant whorls, claiming each duneâlike ridge mirrored the coils of fate. Hellenistic manuals tally portents in drifting siltâforked lines presaged quarrel, concentric rings a safe voyageâwhile lateâRoman necromancers prized the cremains of nobles, believing the dead whispered by way of their own soot. Byzantine penitentials still condemn âdustâlettersâ traced at crossroads to discover thieves, hinting the craft survived beneath ecclesiastical censure. Renaissance occultists revived the art in alchemical ateliers, sieving pulverized bone onto black glass to chart planetary conjunctions. Even modern mythic lore cites artists like Jacksonâ¯Pollock, whose paintâspatter âreadingsâ echoed the old dust sigils.",
