      "notes": "Overview\r\nKliestiepappio sits majestically atop Brokopondo Reservoir in Suriname, with wooden bridges spanning its waters to connect various buildings and repurposed barges. Primarily serving students from the Caribbean and the Guianas, the campus is renowned for its vivid integration of natural water elements and culturally steeped traditions. Uniquely, it is one of the few schools worldwide that teaches the Dark Arts alongside traditional wand casting. The setting itself inspires a curriculum where local spirit lore informs every spell and flight.\r\n\r\nTraditions\r\nWinti:The AfroâSurinamese spiritual tradition emphasizing community rituals, ancestral veneration, secret chants, and healing ceremonies. Its influence is woven into Charms through traditional incantations, Creature studies via ancestral spirit lore, and Defense classes with protective warding spells drawn from Winti rites.\r\nArawak Spirit Lore:Indigenous mysticism that honors natureâs rhythms, transformation cycles, and divination through earth and water. This tradition enriches Transfiguration with motifs of natural metamorphosis, inspires Flying with lessons on wind and water currents, and guides Creature studies by interpreting native fauna through intuitive, earth-bound divination.\r\nKanaima Binding:A controlled practice of dark magic rooted in regional lore, teaching ethical restraint and the transformation of shadow energy. Kanaima principles are central to the Dark Artsâwhere structured shadow-binding techniques are masteredâand inform Defense classes with countermeasures grounded in ethical applications of dark magic.\r\nMaroon Mysticism:A syncretic tradition from Maroon communities that emphasizes resilience, communal strength, and transformative renewal. This tradition infuses Charms with empowering oral traditions, guides Transfiguration with themes of renewal and identity, informs Potions through local herbal lore, and shapes Defense strategies inspired by Maroon protective practices.\r\n\r\nArchitecture\r\nKliestiepappioâs campus embodies a harmonious blend of natural design and cultural storytelling. Wooden bridges suspended gracefully over the waters of Brokopondo Reservoir serve not only as functional connections between various buildings but also as symbolic links between the realms of tradition. Repurposed barges host classrooms and specialized practice areas, creating intimate environments that echo the fluidity of water and the ever-changing nature of magic. At the heart of the campus stands the Ancestral Pavilionâa central gathering hall, richly adorned with carvings and motifs drawn from Winti and Arawak iconography, where communal rites and scholarly exchanges are held under open skies.\r\n\r\nAreas Served\r\nKliestiepappio primarily caters to students from the Caribbean Islands and the Guianas. This diverse student body is deeply connected to the local occult heritage and regional cultural practices, ensuring that the school remains a vibrant crossroads of magical traditions from across the region.",
      "notes-value": "<h3 class=\"\" data-start=\"585\" data-end=\"597\">Overview</h3>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"598\" data-end=\"1143\">Kliestiepappio sits majestically atop Brokopondo Reservoir in Suriname, with wooden bridges spanning its waters to connect various buildings and repurposed barges. Primarily serving students from the Caribbean and the Guianas, the campus is renowned for its vivid integration of natural water elements and culturally steeped traditions. Uniquely, it is one of the few schools worldwide that teaches the Dark Arts alongside traditional wand casting. The setting itself inspires a curriculum where local spirit lore informs every spell and flight.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 data-start=\"147\" data-end=\"161\"><strong data-start=\"147\" data-end=\"161\">Traditions</strong></h3>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"163\" data-end=\"495\"><strong data-start=\"163\" data-end=\"173\">Winti:</strong><br data-start=\"173\" data-end=\"176\" />The AfroâSurinamese spiritual tradition emphasizing community rituals, ancestral veneration, secret chants, and healing ceremonies. Its influence is woven into Charms through traditional incantations, Creature studies via ancestral spirit lore, and Defense classes with protective warding spells drawn from Winti rites.</p>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"497\" data-end=\"871\"><strong data-start=\"497\" data-end=\"520\">Arawak Spirit Lore:</strong><br data-start=\"520\" data-end=\"523\" />Indigenous mysticism that honors natureâs rhythms, transformation cycles, and divination through earth and water. This tradition enriches Transfiguration with motifs of natural metamorphosis, inspires Flying with lessons on wind and water currents, and guides Creature studies by interpreting native fauna through intuitive, earth-bound divination.</p>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"873\" data-end=\"1224\"><strong data-start=\"873\" data-end=\"893\">Kanaima Binding:</strong><br data-start=\"893\" data-end=\"896\" />A controlled practice of dark magic rooted in regional lore, teaching ethical restraint and the transformation of shadow energy. Kanaima principles are central to the Dark Artsâwhere structured shadow-binding techniques are masteredâand inform Defense classes with countermeasures grounded in ethical applications of dark magic.</p>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"1226\" data-end=\"1607\"><strong data-start=\"1226\" data-end=\"1247\">Maroon Mysticism:</strong><br data-start=\"1247\" data-end=\"1250\" />A syncretic tradition from Maroon communities that emphasizes resilience, communal strength, and transformative renewal. This tradition infuses Charms with empowering oral traditions, guides Transfiguration with themes of renewal and identity, informs Potions through local herbal lore, and shapes Defense strategies inspired by Maroon protective practices.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 data-start=\"1692\" data-end=\"1708\"><strong data-start=\"1692\" data-end=\"1708\">Architecture</strong></h3>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"1710\" data-end=\"2413\">Kliestiepappioâs campus embodies a harmonious blend of natural design and cultural storytelling. Wooden bridges suspended gracefully over the waters of Brokopondo Reservoir serve not only as functional connections between various buildings but also as symbolic links between the realms of tradition. Repurposed barges host classrooms and specialized practice areas, creating intimate environments that echo the fluidity of water and the ever-changing nature of magic. At the heart of the campus stands the Ancestral Pavilionâa central gathering hall, richly adorned with carvings and motifs drawn from Winti and Arawak iconography, where communal rites and scholarly exchanges are held under open skies.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 data-start=\"2420\" data-end=\"2436\"><strong data-start=\"2420\" data-end=\"2436\">Areas Served</strong></h3>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"2438\" data-end=\"2733\">Kliestiepappio primarily caters to students from the Caribbean Islands and the Guianas. This diverse student body is deeply connected to the local occult heritage and regional cultural practices, ensuring that the school remains a vibrant crossroads of magical traditions from across the region.</p>",
