      "notes": "Overview\r\nAiccokrea is Central Africaâs most respected wizarding academy. Cut into the sheer cliffs of the Kaboboâ¯Massif and linked by vineâhung bridges to terraces above Lakeâ¯Tanganyika, the school teaches disciplined wandâcasting anchored in regional ritual practice. Early study is broadâstudents master protective nkisi enchantments, lunar divination, and ritual herbâharvestâbefore narrowing to advanced scholarship in Yearsâ¯4â7.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPhilosophy\r\n\r\n \tNkisi Craft & Defensive Duty â Wizards are guardians; they learn to bind iron, wood, and herb charges into nkisi bundles that protect communities and punish wrongdoing.\r\n \t\r\nSacredâMountain & Lake Ethics â The massifâs forests and Tanganyikaâs depths are taboo zones; harvesting or creature work follows strict ritual etiquette to keep natural and spirit worlds in balance.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nArchitecture\r\nAiccokrea is perched high in the Kaboboâ¯Massifâs montane forest, its entire campus built into the canopy of towering red mahogany and African yellowâwood trees. Three sturdy, railed walkways form concentric rings around the trunks, linked by simple lifts and ladders. Ironârune collars secure platforms without harming the living wood, keeping classrooms, dorms, greenhouses, and a small forge deck safely suspended above the forest floor.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAreasâ¯Served\r\nAiccokrea admits students from the DRC, Rwanda, Burundi, Tanzania, Zambia, and Malawi, with a small cohort from wider Central Africa drawn by its reputation for ironâhard defensive magic and rigorous history scholarship.",
